</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>18304090936228740235</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02154838240142105701</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>06846277367930685297</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>12330684148828250557</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13157417834919791728</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13238795384739770663</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>05786170937782202010</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13355597379946163116</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>09155909162256028654</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>06465831671706382036</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>12418555914107204786</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>04114300074411396771</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11601834169198869464</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>14943379505489023993</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>09266877898802741706</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>17096450717718855714</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>14408720482092483775</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>09821941377184152447</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>14457473046109904699</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>04135601886946074481</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>12820014720721423266</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02431435883551802545</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13659463864430149651</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>02663785788542409357</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11364658987488258139</gr:likingUser><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://rss1.smashingmagazine.com/feed/"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://rss1.smashingmagazine.com/feed/</id><title type="html">Smashing Magazine Feed</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://www.smashingmagazine.com/" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1314901367826"><id gr:original-id="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/?p=272">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/ad2b2f0b5366634b</id><category term="Popular Culture/Society"/><category term="Teaching/Theory"/><category term="Uncategorized"/><category term="adult development"/><category term="Bernard Malamud"/><category term="constructive developmental theory"/><category term="Hasidism"/><category term="holding environment"/><category term="human development"/><category term="humanistic psychology"/><category term="Martin Buber"/><category term="personal development"/><category term="Peter Pruyn"/><category term="Robert Kegan"/><category term="Saul Bellow"/><category term="subject object"/><category term="subject object relations"/><category term="subject object reversal"/><category term="sweeter welcome"/><title type="html">A Taste of The Sweeter Welcome</title><published>2011-08-31T00:45:02Z</published><updated>2011-08-31T00:45:02Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/2011/08/31/a-taste-of-the-sweeter-welcome/" type="text/html"/><content xml:base="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/feed/" type="html">&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/files/2011/08/Sweeter-Welcome.png"&gt;&lt;img src="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/files/2011/08/Sweeter-Welcome.png" alt="" width="150" height="224"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.gse.harvard.edu/directory/faculty/faculty-detail/?fc=318&amp;amp;flt=k&amp;amp;sub=all"&gt;Robert Kegan&lt;/a&gt; occasionally makes fleeting reference to the fact that &lt;em&gt;The Evolving Self&lt;/em&gt; was not his first book.  His first book, &lt;em&gt;The Sweeter Welcome&lt;/em&gt;, is both little and big.  It is little in that is it physically small and short in length; it is big in that it spans literature, religion and spirituality, hinted at in the subtitle: &lt;em&gt;Voices for a Vision of Affirmation: Bellow, Malamud and Martin Buber&lt;/em&gt;.  Kegan has also derisively noted that only two people have ever read it.  As if to corroborate this claim, the library copy I read had copious marginalia in pencil–that abruptly stopped on page 29.  I suppose I can now claim to have increased this readership by 50%.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Why read such a book?  I am interested in the history of science.  How does one’s life experience come to influence one’s work?  What is the substrate from which theories grow?  &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Piaget#Biography"&gt;Piaget&lt;/a&gt; was inspired by childrens’ wrong answers on standardized tests.  Some of &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein#Patent_office"&gt;the electronics patents Einstein worked on in the Swiss patent office&lt;/a&gt; may have influenced his later thought experiments about relativity.  So, I was curious to ask the question, “From whence &lt;a href="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/2010/06/09/an-overview-of-constructive-developmental-theory-cdt/"&gt;CDT&lt;/a&gt;?”  While one small book would not answer such a question completely, I wondered what I would find.  As such, this is not meant to be an objective book review; I was deliberately looking for potential connections between this literary and spiritual work and Kegan’s future psychological work that was to come.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Published in 1976, six years prior to &lt;em&gt;The Evolving Self&lt;/em&gt;, Kegan explains &lt;em&gt;The Sweeter Welcome&lt;/em&gt; had its origins in work he did as a Senior Fellow at Dartmouth College.  It was also informed, however, by his and his wife’s experience of living for several months in the &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lubavitch"&gt;Lubavitch Hasidic Community&lt;/a&gt; in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, a community he defines as seeking the “integration of the intellectual and theoretic into the ecstatic ‘hallowing of the everyday’” (pp. 1, 157).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Kegan explains his choice of title in the introduction:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:30px"&gt;
&lt;em&gt;“In the third act of &lt;/em&gt;Macbeth&lt;em&gt;, the King convenes a dinner party, and then, with proper pomp and plurals, excuses himself from the preliminaries:&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:60px"&gt;
‘To make society the sweeter welcome&lt;br&gt;
We will keep ourselves till supper-time alone’ (III. i. 42-43)
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:30px"&gt;
&lt;em&gt;The sweetness of community after the lean loneliness of its absence: that is what this book is about” (p. 4).&lt;/em&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Specifically, &lt;em&gt;The Sweeter Welcome&lt;/em&gt; engages in a dialogue between three parties: the writings of the Jewish philosopher &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Buber"&gt;Martin Buber&lt;/a&gt;, the mystical traditions of Hasidism, and the main characters in four novels: &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Bellow"&gt;Saul Bellow&lt;/a&gt;‘s &lt;em&gt;Henderson the Rain King&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;The Adventures of Augie March&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Malamud"&gt;Bernard Malamud&lt;/a&gt;‘s &lt;em&gt;The Assistant&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;The Fixer&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I would describe the central theme as the exploration of how community can act as a &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Winnicott#The_concept_of_holding"&gt;holding environment&lt;/a&gt; for the development of the protagonists in each of the four novels.  A foundational feature of such a slow and sometimes painful process is Buber’s &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I-Thou"&gt;&lt;em&gt;I-Thou&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; formulation of fulfilling relationships; that is, the recognition of the other as a &lt;em&gt;Thou&lt;/em&gt; as opposed to an objectified &lt;em&gt;It&lt;/em&gt;.  Quoting Buber, Kegan writes, “The world and I are mutually included, the one in the other.  This contradiction in thought, inherent in the situation of &lt;em&gt;It&lt;/em&gt;, is resolved in the situation of &lt;em&gt;Thou&lt;/em&gt;, which sets men free from the world in order to bind men up in solidarity of connection with it” (p. 62).  “For the inmost growth of the self is not accomplished, as people like to suppose today, in man’s relation to himself, but in the relation between the one and the other, between men, that is, pre-eminently in the mutuality of the making present” (p.134).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The particular classroom Bellow and Malamud choose to teach such lessons is the novel.  Quoting &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DH_Lawrence"&gt;D.H. Lawrence&lt;/a&gt;, Kegan observes, “The essential function of art…is not aesthetic but moral” (p. 32).  Through their characters “Bellow and Malamud design anew the idea that the novel dwells in the particular to make its way to the universal” (p. 137).  Specifically, the combined journeys of their characters illustrate “the feeling of the community of existence.  To feel the universal generation as a sea and oneself as a wave in it, this is the mystery of humility” (p. 21).  Human development occurs as “The characters…have to work upon the world to make it yield its holy sparks, to release their own” (p. 138).  I see this as a foreshadowing of the kind of subject/object reversals Kegan would later write about: problems that we don’t solve so much as they solve &lt;em&gt;us&lt;/em&gt; (Kegan, 2009:167). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So do I feel that this little/big book sheds some light on the origins of CDT?  Partly.  Kegan has said that he originally developed CDT to try and assist clinicians in working with their clients.  &lt;em&gt;The Sweeter Welcome&lt;/em&gt; provides an intriguing backdrop to such work, namely the literary and the spiritual rather than merely the empirical and psychological.  Kegan elaborates on bridging these two worlds in &lt;a href="http://www.presencing.com/dol/interviews/Kegan-1999.shtml"&gt;a 1999 interview&lt;/a&gt; with &lt;a href="http://www.ottoscharmer.com/bio/"&gt;Otto Scharmer&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:30px"&gt;
&lt;em&gt;“I really wanted to bring lifespan and internal phenomenological and existential dimension to what was otherwise, at some level, a very dry cognitive psychology.
&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:30px"&gt;
At the same time, I felt that &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humanistic_psychology"&gt;humanistic psychology&lt;/a&gt;–which was kind of in mode at that time, asking the bigger questions about life’s meaning, drawing on European philosophy and theology–was asking the biggest questions, but they lacked any real substantive, rigorous, logical driver, internal power.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:30px"&gt;
I wanted to bring these things together and create a richer developmental psychology that was both powerfully descriptive from the outside, but also powerfully descriptive from the inside–the internal experience of being a growing person and thinking about the context and support of development….
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left:30px"&gt;
During those years I had extraordinary spiritual experiences when I realized that I had an unusual connection to both of these fields.”
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don’t think it’s an accident, therefore, how &lt;a href="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/2010/06/09/an-overview-of-constructive-developmental-theory-cdt/#self-transforming"&gt;5th order&lt;/a&gt; so much of Buber and Hasidic ideals sound: “Israel’s prophets, Buber says, ‘always aimed to shatter all security and to proclaim in the opened abyss of the final insecurity the unwished for God who demands that His human creatures become real…the key to this ‘holy insecurity’ is the ‘ever-anew’ of each situation as opposed to the ‘once and for all’ with which man tries to abstract himself from the concrete.’  The key is in the ‘ever-anew,’ that is the say, the novel” (p. 138).  “Ever-anew” sounds to me like another formulation of mindfulness, surely an underpinning of the 5th order value of remaining open as opposed to stuck in habitual states of mind.  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Such developmental aspirations serve as a reminder of the traditional aspiration of religion to create holding environments to further human development.  In Judaism, such aspirations inspire the cultural value of education: “rabbi; the word means teacher, no more” (p. 129).  Just as a novel needs a reader, so, too, a teacher needs a student: “Without the question, there will not be an answer” (p. 140).  All of which leads me back to the first page of &lt;em&gt;The Sweeter Welcome&lt;/em&gt; and my favorite sentence, upon which I will close: &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;“Education is a child of attention, but all attention is at least a mild form of surprise.”&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Peter W. Pruyn</name></author><gr:likingUser>15458801304540236705</gr:likingUser><source gr:stream-id="feed/http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/feed/"><id>tag:google.com,2005:reader/feed/http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/feed/</id><title type="html">Developmental Observer</title><link rel="alternate" href="http://developmentalobserver.blog.com/feed/" type="text/html"/></source></entry><entry gr:crawl-timestamp-msec="1313783983740"><id gr:original-id="http://xkcd.com/940/">tag:google.com,2005:reader/item/c01698afdfc0599e</id><title type="html">Oversight</title><published>2011-08-19T04:00:00Z</published><updated>2011-08-19T04:00:00Z</updated><link rel="alternate" href="http://xkcd.com/940/" type="text/html"/><summary xml:base="http://xkcd.com/" type="html">&lt;img src="http://imgs.xkcd.com/comics/oversight.png" title="I felt so clever when I found a way to game the Fitocracy system by incorporating a set of easy but high-scoring activities into my regular schedule. Took me a bit to realize I&amp;#39;d been tricked into setting up a daily exercise routine." alt="I felt so clever when I found a way to game the Fitocracy system by incorporating a set of easy but high-scoring activities into my regular schedule. Took me a bit to realize I&amp;#39;d been tricked into setting up a daily exercise routine."&gt;</summary><author gr:unknown-author="true"><name>(author unknown)</name></author><gr:likingUser>16132077327717941966</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>15633407758609116626</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>03752144494067576080</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>13615725639700755228</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01378362922825043920</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>16424068017393110348</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>06619280203313515759</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>11919049923671816088</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>01171609223597496348</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>14274384500514150963</gr:likingUser><gr:likingUser>16893483246446677011<